# Laravel Best Practices

## Critical Rules

- Follow Laravel's directory structure and naming conventions:
  - Controllers: `app/Http/Controllers/{Resource}Controller.php`
  - Models: `app/Models/{Singular}.php`
  - Services: `app/Services/{Resource}Service.php`
  - Repositories: `app/Repositories/{Resource}Repository.php`
  - Requests: `app/Http/Requests/{Resource}/{Action}Request.php`
  - Resources: `app/Http/Resources/{Resource}Resource.php`
  - Middleware: `app/Http/Middleware/{Action}.php`
  - Migrations: `database/migrations/{timestamp}_{action}_{table}.php`

- Use Laravel's built-in features and helpers:
  - Use Eloquent ORM instead of raw SQL queries
  - Use Laravel's authentication system (Sanctum, Fortify, etc.)
  - Use Form Request Validation for complex validations
  - Use API Resources for API responses
  - Use Laravel's Queue system for long-running tasks
  - Use Laravel's Cache system for performance optimization

- Follow Service-Repository pattern for complex business logic:
  - Services handle business logic
  - Repositories handle database operations
  - Controllers stay thin and handle HTTP layer only

- Security best practices:
  - Always validate user input using Form Requests
  - Use Laravel's CSRF protection
  - Use prepared statements (default in Eloquent)
  - Hash passwords using Laravel's Hash facade
  - Use Laravel's authentication guards appropriately
  - Implement rate limiting for APIs

- Database and Eloquent:
  - Use migrations for database changes
  - Use seeders and factories for test data
  - Define relationships in models
  - Use model observers for complex model events
  - Use database transactions for critical operations
  - Use eager loading to avoid N+1 problems

- Route organization:
  - Group related routes
  - Use route names for all routes
  - Use route model binding when possible
  - Apply middleware groups appropriately
  - Version your APIs

- Testing:
  - Write feature tests for critical paths
  - Use database factories for test data
  - Use Laravel's testing helpers
  - Test HTTP responses and database states

## Examples

<example>
// Good Controller Example
namespace App\Http\Controllers;

class UserController extends Controller
{
    private $userService;

    public function __construct(UserService $userService)
    {
        $this->userService = $userService;
    }

    public function store(StoreUserRequest $request)
    {
        $user = $this->userService->createUser($request->validated());
        return new UserResource($user);
    }
}

// Good Model Example
namespace App\Models;

class User extends Authenticatable
{
    protected $fillable = ['name', 'email', 'password'];
    protected $hidden = ['password'];

    public function posts()
    {
        return $this->hasMany(Post::class);
    }
}

// Good Service Example
namespace App\Services;

class UserService
{
    private $userRepository;

    public function __construct(UserRepository $userRepository)
    {
        $this->userRepository = $userRepository;
    }

    public function createUser(array $data)
    {
        $data['password'] = Hash::make($data['password']);
        return $this->userRepository->create($data);
    }
}
</example>

<example type="invalid">
// Bad Controller Example - Too Much Logic
class UserController extends Controller
{
    public function store(Request $request)
    {
        $request->validate([
            'name' => 'required',
            'email' => 'required|email',
            'password' => 'required|min:8'
        ]);

        $user = User::create([
            'name' => $request->name,
            'email' => $request->email,
            'password' => bcrypt($request->password)
        ]);

        // Business logic in controller
        $this->sendWelcomeEmail($user);
        $this->createUserProfile($user);

        return response()->json($user);
    }
}

// Bad Model Example - Too Much Logic
class User extends Model
{
    public function someComplexOperation()
    {
        // Business logic in model
        if ($this->isSpecialUser()) {
            $this->processSpecialUser();
        }
        $this->updateLastLogin();
        $this->sendNotification();
    }
}

// Bad Route Example
Route::post('/users', function (Request $request) {
    // Logic directly in route
    $user = User::create($request->all());
    return $user;
});
</example>
